TY  - JOUR
AB  - In a memorandum by tax expert of the fourteenth century we find discussed some very modern problems. The point at issue was whether a piece of land that had reverted from pasture to cultivation could be assessed to the local general property tax at a higher figure. The argument in opposition was based primarily on the fact that a new use of the land was due to the efforts and outlay of the cultivator, who ought therefore not to be penalized. Our expert decides, however, to the contrary effect for two primary reasons. In first place, a distinction must be made between land other than property. Personal property is, indeed, to be assessed at its selling value; but in the case of land, the real test is the annual produce or yield value, which does not always immediately reflect in selling value. Since land should be assessed according to its yield rather than according to the selling value, this particular plot may be taken up in the assessment list at the higher figure. In the second place, a distinction is made between a special property tax or a land tax in rem and a general property tax. In the case of a tax in rem, it is proper to take account of the expenses or outlay. But a generl property tax is a personal tax upon the individual according to his ability to pay; and it is incontestable that his ability to pay has been increased by his utilization of the land. The conclusion is that the officials were entirely justified in increasing the assesment.
